Document: Using GridMaps
Path: godot/tutorials/3d/using_gridmaps.rst
Summary: This section explains how to create a MeshLibrary for use with GridMaps in Godot.
Creating a MeshLibrary
To begin, you need a MeshLibrary, which is a collection of individual meshes that can be used in the gridmap. Open the "mesh_library_source.tscn" scene to see an example of how to set up the mesh library.

As you can see, this scene has a Node3D node as its root, and a number of MeshInstance3D node children.

If you don't need any physics in your scene, then you're done. However, in most cases you'll want to assign collision bodies to the meshes.
---CHUNK---
Document: using_gridmaps.rst
Path: godot/tutorials/3d/using_gridmaps.rst
Summary: This section explains how to add collision shapes to meshes within a GridMap.
Collisions
You can manually assign a StaticBody3D and CollisionShape3D to each mesh. Alternatively, you can use the "Mesh" menu to automatically create the collision body based on the mesh data. Note that a "Convex" collision body will work better for simple meshes. For more complex shapes, select "Create Trimesh Static Body". Once each mesh has a physics body and collision shape assigned, your mesh library is ready to be used.
---CHUNK---
Document: Using GridMaps
Path: godot/tutorials/3d/using_gridmaps.rst
Summary: This section explains how materials are handled in GridMaps.
Materials are only taken from within the meshes themselves when generating the mesh library. Materials that are set directly on the GridMap node are ignored.
---CHUNK---
Document: using_gridmaps.rst
Path: godot/tutorials/3d/using_gridmaps.rst
Summary: This section explains how to use NavigationMeshes with GridMaps for 3D navigation.
NavigationMeshes
Like all mesh instances, MeshLibrary items can be assigned a NavigationMesh resource, which can be created manually, or baked.

To create the NavigationMesh from a MeshLibrary scene export, place a NavigationRegion3D child node below the main MeshInstance3D for the GridMap item. Add a valid NavigationMesh resource to the NavigationRegion3D and some source geometry nodes below and bake the NavigationMesh.

Note: With small grid cells it is often necessary to reduce the NavigationMesh properties for agent radius and region minimum size.

Nodes below the NavigationRegion3D are ignored for the MeshLibrary scene export, so additional nodes can be added as source geometry just for baking the navmesh.

Warning: The baked cell size of the NavigationMesh must match the NavigationServer map cell size to properly merge the navigation meshes of different grid cells.
---CHUNK---
Document: using_gridmaps.rst
Path: godot/tutorials/3d/using_gridmaps.rst
Summary: This section explains how to bake lightmaps onto GridMaps, including how UV2 data is handled and how to configure texel size.
Lightmaps
It is possible to bake lightmaps onto a GridMap. Lightmap UV2 data will be reused from meshes if already present. If UV2 data is not present, then it will be automatically generated on bake with a lightmap texel size of 0.1 units. To generate UV2 data with a different lightmap texel size, you can set the global illumination mode in the Import dock to Static Lightmaps and specify the texel size there. This option must be changed before the scene is converted to a MeshLibrary, as changing it later on will not affect the existing MeshLibrary data.

Aside from this peculiarity, the lightmap baking process is the same as for any other 3D scene. See using_lightmap_gi for more information about lightmap baking.
---CHUNK---
Document: using_gridmaps.rst
Path: godot/tutorials/3d/using_gridmaps.rst
Summary: This section details the specific node structure required for a MeshLibrary scene in Godot.

A MeshLibrary scene must have a Node3D as its root. Its children define the items within the MeshLibrary. Each child node must adhere to the following:
* It must be a MeshInstance3D. This MeshInstance3D will be the visual mesh exported as a MeshLibrary item.
* It must have a material assigned to its mesh's material slot, not the MeshInstance3D's own material slots.
* It can have at most one StaticBody3D child for collision. This StaticBody3D must contain one or more CollisionShape3D children.
* It can have at most one NavigationRegion3D child for navigation. This NavigationRegion3D can include additional MeshInstance3D children, which can be used for baking navigation data but will not be exported as visual meshes.

Only nodes structured in this exact format will be recognized and exported by GridMap. Other node types added as children will be ignored. GridMap is specifically designed for placing meshes with associated collision and navigation data on a grid, not for general node placement.
---CHUNK---
