Document: Using GridMaps
Path: godot/tutorials/3d/using_gridmaps.rst
Summary: Overview of GridMap Inspector properties including physics, cell sizing, collision settings, and navigation baking.

Inspector properties

The Physics Material setting allows you to override the physics material for every mesh in the NavigationMesh.

Under Cells, the Size property should be set to the size of your meshes. You can leave it at the default value for the demo. Uncheck the Center Y property.

The Collision options allow you to set the collision layer, collision mask, and priority for the entire grid. For more information on how those work see the Physics Introduction section.

Under Navigation is the Bake Navigation option. If enabled it creates a navigation region for each cell that uses a mesh library item with a navigation mesh.

If you click on the MeshLibrary itself in the inspector you can adjust settings for individual meshes, such as their navigation mesh, navigation layers, or if the mesh casts shadows.
---CHUNK---
Document: using_gridmaps.rst
Path: godot/tutorials/3d/using_gridmaps.rst
Summary: Describes the GridMap panel tools and settings in the Godot editor.
The GridMap panel is located at the bottom of the editor and typically opens automatically when a GridMap node is added. The toolbar within this panel offers various tools for manipulating grid-based meshes:

- Transform: Adds a gizmo to the scene for changing the relative position and rotation of the GridMap.
- Selection: Enables selecting an area in the viewport, allowing for multi-space selection by clicking and dragging.
- Erase: When active, clicking in the viewport deletes selected meshes.
- Paint: When active, clicking in the viewport adds the currently selected mesh from the GridMap panel to the scene.
- Pick: When active, clicking on a GridMap mesh in the viewport selects it in the GridMap panel.
- Fill: Fills a selected area in the viewport with the mesh currently selected in the GridMap panel.
- Move: Moves the currently selected mesh or meshes in the viewport.
- Duplicate: Creates a copy of the selected mesh or meshes in the GridMap.
- Delete: Deletes the entire selected area, similar to the Erase tool but for a larger region.
- Cursor Rotate X: When the paint tool is selected, this rotates the mesh to be painted on the X-axis. It also rotates selected areas if they are being moved.
- Cursor Rotate Y: When the paint tool is selected, this rotates the mesh to be painted on the Y-axis. It also rotates selected areas if they are being moved.
- Cursor Rotate Z: When the paint tool is selected, this rotates the mesh to be painted on the Z-axis. It also rotates selected areas if they are being moved.
- Change Grid Floor: Adjusts the current floor being worked on, which can be changed using arrows or by typing a value.
- Filter Meshes: Used to search for a specific mesh within the bottom panel.
- Zoom: Controls the zoom level for meshes displayed in the bottom panel.
- Layout toggles: Two buttons that switch between different layout arrangements for meshes in the bottom panel.
- Tools dropdown: Opens a menu containing additional options.

Within the Tools dropdown, clicking on Settings opens a window where the Pick Distance can be adjusted. The Pick Distance defines the maximum distance from the camera (in meters) at which tiles can be placed on a GridMap.
---CHUNK---
